But in reality, the problem states that a configuration is good if there are no two arrows forming a clockwise quadrangle. So in the first pairing (A-B, C-D), the arrows are AB and CD. The quadrangle is A-B-C-D, which is clockwise. So both arrows AB and CD are present. Therefore, this configuration is invalid. The second pairing (A-C, B-D) is valid because the only arrows are AC and BD, which are not part of any clockwise quadrangle. So for n=2, the number of good configurations is 1. The problem states: "there are no two arrows AB and CD such that ABCD is a convex quadrangle oriented clockwise." So in the first pairing (A-B, C-D), the four points A, B, C, D form a convex quadrangle (since they are in order around the circle), and the arrows AB and CD are present. Therefore, this configuration is invalid. The second pairing (A-C, B-D) has arrows AC and BD. The quadrangle A-B-C-D has edges AB, BC, CD, DA. The arrows AC and BD are not edges of this quadrangle.
